name: Colorado Technology Sales Meetup
description:
We are a select group of Technology Sales Professionals who meet to discuss our careers, projects, sales skills and day-to-day sales efforts within Colorado. We are fostering an exclusive group of technology sales professionals who complement each other and can help enable each other, rather than compete with each other.  Admission into our group is not guaranteed.  In order to maximize the benefit our members gain from the group, we are selective with the intent of avoiding having competing sales professionals in the same room.  We will avoid having multiple professionals representing similar product or services. (i.e. multiple database products, storage infrastructure, etc)

FUTURE TOPICS: 

1. Other networking events

2. Bring us your insurmountable sales problem and lets discuss

3. Closing techniques

4. What mobile apps (or desktop apps) do you find useful for Sales, CRM, business info, etc.?

5. Prospecting

6. Sales 'Book of the month club'

7. Handling Objections

8. Relationship Building best practices

9. Closing

10. How to secure Referrals from your book of business

11. Service After the Sale

12. Loyalty & Retention

Oh, and we have ice cold beer and hot baked pizza, too.  A different Colorado brewery will be featured each month.

name: Denver Supply Chain Analytics Group
description: This groups if for anyone who wants to improve their supply chain operations. It's a place for practitioners meet with people facing similar issues, and find out what is working for others. We discuss practical (not pie in the sky theory) applications and techniques for visualizing and optimizing operations by using the data we have available from our ERP systems. The group focuses on solving problems, and topics for the next meetup are created from group feedback on what would be most helpful.

name: Boulder Jenkins Area Meetup
description: Jenkins is the premier open source technology for implementing Agile continuous integration, continuous delivery, and DevOps practices. This group will connect professionals in the pursuit of sharing practices, networking, and exploring advanced topics.

name: Denver Area Umbraco Meetup
description: Calling all Denver/Boulder and surrounding area Umbracians. The Denver Umbraco Meetup is a meetup for the worlds friendliest open source CMS and the people who love it or those that just want to learn more. Lets get together and chat about Umbraco and build a strong Colorado Umbraco community. All skill levels welcome from certified developer to I have never built a website before. "Umbraco is a fully-featured open source content management system with the flexibility to run anything from small campaign or brochure sites right through to complex applications for Fortune 500's and some of the largest media sites in the world."

name: SherlockΩs
description:
This group is for folks interested in hacking on hardware and robotics and sharing their findings and experiences with other Denver Makers. We will focus on creating and teaching in a fun and relaxed environment. Our goal is to explore together the vast and exciting space , the makers movement has inspired, ranging from the practical to the artsy as well as the silly.

All are welcome!!

Follow us: @ohmsio

name: Colorado Customer Success Meetup
description: If you're a cloud computing (SaaS, IaaS, PaaS, MSP, mobile) manager whose mission is to onboard, serve, retain, and grow customer relationships, this Meetup is for you! Join us for terrific networking, learning, and sharing ideas to combat customer churn and increase loyalty. We're a local chapter of the Customer Success Association. Topics include new technologies, "best practices," management systems, and people dynamics. Attendance is free and all are welcome.

name: Boulder Developer (& Designer) Collaborative
description: Working to create a space for tech creators (programmers, designers, etc.), and a community that's focused around startups, learning, work, collaboration, and fun.

name: Geospatial Amateurs - Denver
description: Geospatial Amateurs is a monthly meetup to discuss topics around web mapping, geospatial applications and data. We are focused on new generation technologies, not "old school GIS" - as the name suggests, we are not "GIS professionals" :). But all are welcome to discuss and share new ways of developing geospatial applications! We plan to meet monthly in rotating venues around central Denver, have a couple of short presentations, networking time and a fun and informal atmosphere.

name: Boulder/Denver Spark Meetup
description: Apache Spark is a popular big data processing engine and ecosystem with a strong and growing community. This group is for people in the greater Denver area interested in learning more about Spark's capabilities, use cases, and integration with other Big Data tools as well as engaging with the larger Spark community.

name: Denver Creative Tech
description:
Calling all creative coders, 3d modelers, game developers, hardware hackers, new media artists, frontend devs, motion graphics animators, musicians, illustrators and anyone else across the creative technology spectrum. We're hosting monthly meetups with short talks from a diverse set of professionals, educators and enthusiasts on a wide range of tools and theories behind our multidisciplinary crafts. Come expand your mind and meet your fellow high-tech creatives.

We realized there are so many amazing people doing amazing things with creative technology in Colorado, but no official community to connect them. We're hoping to fill the gaps and build some bridges to learn about new techniques, get inspired, and meet potential collaborators.

Come down and geek out with your people!

http://CreativeTe.ch

name: Ansible Denver
description:
We are a group of Systems Engineers and DevOps folks who want to Ansible all the things. Want to learn more about Ansible? Come join us. Already know Ansible well? Come share your knowledge.

Threw up a github repo for code samples, examples, presentations, or just general notes!

https://github.com/rguiliani/ansible-denver-meetup

name: Colorado Containers
description: Containerization has swept the technology landscape with simple tooling and great developer experience, but making the jump from your laptop to production can be a daunting task. Dealing with multi-host networking, service discovery, log aggregation, developer authentication and operational complexity can be an uphill battle if you go it alone. Join us to stay up to date on all things Containers including demos, workshops, and tutorials! Technologies we are interested in exploring include: CI/CD, scheduling, orchestration, overlay networks, monitoring, cluster operations, and application development patters like micro-services.

name: Front Range Apache Kafka
description: This group is for everyone interested in Kafka and the Kafka ecosystem. The Kafka broker, Kafka Streaming, Kafka Connect, The Confluent Data Platform, Apache Avro and anything else that publishes to and subscribes from Kafka. Kafka is a critical part of any high throughput data and analytics platform and a great general messaging platform. Come learn from others about how to provision, run, scale and connect to this popular open-source messaging platform.

name: Kids Develop It!
description:
KIDS DEVELOP IT!

Kids Develop It! is for everyone who wants to help kids and youth use technology creatively - educators, developers, parents, and kids! We'll meet to share ideas and experiences, learn new applications, and empower kids to use technology to tell their own story.  Our launch party will be September 25, 2014 at the Google offices in Boulder (2590 Pearl St).  We'll have demonstrations, short presentations of tech tools that are accessible by kids, and raffle prizes donated by our sponsors.  Please RSVP for the event, space is limited.

name: Denver.rb
description:
We’re a software users group interested in the programming language, Ruby. Our talks range from specific aspects of Ruby on Rails to metaprogamming to anything else in the Ruby world. Occasionally we may talk about software topics not directly tied to Ruby. - I stole that from BoulderRuby cause they said it so well. :)

Denver.rb Code of Conduct

Summary
Harassment in code and discussion or violation of physical boundaries is completely unacceptable anywhere in Denver.rb meetups, project codebases, issue trackers, chatrooms, mailing lists, and other events. Violators will be warned by the group organizers. Repeat violations will result in being blocked or banned by the organizers at or before the 3rd violation.

In detail
Harassment includes offensive verbal comments related to gender identity, gender expression, sexual orientation, disability, physical appearance, body size, race, religion, sexual images, deliberate intimidation, stalking, sustained disruption, and unwelcome sexual attention.

Individuals asked to stop any harassing behavior are expected to comply immediately.

Organizers are also subject to the anti-harassment policy.

If anyone engages in harassing behavior, including organizers, we may take appropriate action, up to and including warning the offender, deletion of comments, removal from the meetup and meetup's codebases, and escalation to Meetup support.

If you are being harassed, notice that someone else is being harassed, or have any other concerns, please contact an organizer of the group immediately.

We expect everyone to follow these rules anywhere in Denver.rb venues, project codebases, issue trackers, chatrooms, and mailing lists.

Finally, don't forget that it is human to make mistakes! We all do. Let’s work together to help each other, resolve issues, and learn from the mistakes that we will all inevitably make from time to time.

Thanks
Thanks to the thoughtbot Open Source Code of Conduct for inspiration.

To the extent possible under law, Denver.rb has waived all copyright and related or neighboring rights to Denver.rb Code of Conduct. This work is published from the United States.

name: Denver MuleSoft User Group
description: The Denver MuleSoft User Group is a group for anyone using or interested in MuleSoft's technologies, Mule ESB, Anypoint Studio, enterprise integration, web services, IoT, REST APIs, microservices, and modern technologies.

name: Full Stack
description:
Full Stack Meetup is a place for developers to learn about emerging and interesting technologies since 2012. Providing high quality food, drinks and talks in a beautiful venue. Come hang out!

Full Stack Code of Conduct

Summary Harassment in code and discussion or violation of physical boundaries is completely unacceptable anywhere in Full Stack meetups, project codebases, issue trackers, chatrooms, mailing lists, and other events. Violators will be warned by the group organizers. Repeat violations will result in being blocked or banned by the organizers at or before the 3rd violation.

In detail Harassment includes offensive verbal comments related to gender identity, gender expression, sexual orientation, disability, physical appearance, body size, race, religion, sexual images, deliberate intimidation, stalking, sustained disruption, and unwelcome sexual attention.

Individuals asked to stop any harassing behavior are expected to comply immediately.

Organizers are also subject to the anti-harassment policy.

If anyone engages in harassing behavior, including organizers, we may take appropriate action, up to and including warning the offender, deletion of comments, removal from the meetup and meetup's codebases, and escalation to Meetup support.

If you are being harassed, notice that someone else is being harassed, or have any other concerns, please contact an organizer of the group immediately.

We expect everyone to follow these rules anywhere in Full Stack venues, project codebases, issue trackers, chatrooms, and mailing lists.

Finally, don't forget that it is human to make mistakes! We all do. Let’s work together to help each other, resolve issues, and learn from the mistakes that we will all inevitably make from time to time.

To the extent possible under law, Full Stack has waived all copyright and related or neighboring rights to Full Stack Code of Conduct. This work is published from the United States.

name: Denver Splunk Meetup
description: This is a group for anyone interested in connecting and collaborating with users of SPLUNK.

name: Denver Data Masters Meetup
description: As a Data Master you are an industry professional who has responsibility at your respective organization for Big Data, advanced analytics, BI, modern data architecture and integration, data visualization, data virtualization, data discovery, data governance, and work with these technologies on a daily basis. Join Radiant Advisors as we deliver and present our latest innovative, cutting-edge research and thought-leadership findings. Join us afterwards for refreshments and stimulating data discussions.

name: Rocky Mountain AngularJS
description: This is a group devoted to the exploration, understanding, and practical application of the AngularJS development framework. We'll organize regularly scheduled meetings that dive deep into every aspect of AngularJS, its place in the development ecosystem, and provide an opportunities to learn the best way possible... by coding with our peers. We welcome developers, managers, designers, and anyone else who is interested learning more about the "Superheroic JavaScript MVW Framework" from Google.

name: Techstars Tech Time
description: Idea is to have informal software/hardware technical discussions in the community.

name: DevOps Exchange DTC Meetup
description: The DevOps Exchange DTC is dedicated to DevOps, System Administrators, Developers, Operations, Software/Infrastructure Automation and Configuration Management professionals, Entrepreneurs, Students and anyone else interested in exchanging ideas related to everything DevOps. This User Group is ideal for anyone that lives and/or works in the Denver Tech Center (DTC) or south of Denver. It is free for users to register and participate. There will be monthly meetings topics ranging from Automation and Configuration management tools like Jenkins, Puppet, Chef, Cloud Foundry, Docker, AWS, Azure, and Bluemix. Not to mention, Test Automation coverage with Selenium, cucumber and Junit. Lastly, we will include Service Management with Service Now. We welcome new presentation ideas and contributions from our participants.

name: Colorado Eloqua Users
description: This group is for users of the Eloqua marketing automation platform in Colorado. Let's get together and share ideas and techniques to optimize our marketing automation efforts and grow our business. Network with other Eloquans, get your marketing automation questions answered, and share your expertise with the community.

name: GeoWest - networking, startups, Geo
description:
GeoWest is for Colorado entrepreneurs, students, developers, investors, and leaders who are (or want to be) involved in the global location, mapping, and geospatial information economy.

GeoWest is a network to connect skills, technologies, market demand, and funding streams.

We expect to make GeoWest a thriving ecosystem to grow the place of Colorado in the global economy.

name: TIBCO Denver Users Group
description: This is a group for anyone interested in exploring, learning, or sharing all things TIBCO Spotfire, Jaspersoft, Mashery, BusinessWorks, and more. We look forward to creating a User community in the Denver Metro and surrounding areas that will encourage exchange of best practices, exploration opportunities for future users, and networking with fellow users, all in a casual atmosphere.

name: Distributed Computing Denver
description: The purpose of this group is to explore the various concepts, practices, and technologies related to distributed computing. Our goals are to provide a platform for the local community to discuss these topics, provide learning resources, and invoke thoughtful conversation. The meetings will cater to newcomers and experts alike... everyone is welcome.

name: Blockstack Denver
description: Blockstack Denver is for developers, designers and entrepreneurs who are passionate about decentralization and open source software. It's for anyone interested in the technology behind Blockstack, which enables a new way of building distributed, server-less applications.

name: Boulder Linux Users Group (BLUG)
description: The Boulder Linux Users Group is a group of hobbyists, professionals and enthusiasts from all walks of life joined by a common interest in using, administering, or developing Free Software for Linux-based operating systems since 1996. See our web site at http://lug.boulder.co.us/

name: Denver Hack Nite
description:
We're open for all forms of hacking. Software and hardware. If you are software developer, engineer, or tinkerer of technology, you are welcome to join us.

www.hacknite.com

name: Full Stack Boulder
description: A group for web professionals and newbies. From rich client user interfaces to multi cluster server deployments. Let's explore together what the web technologies have to offer.

name: Colorado Big Data Enthusiasts
description: "Big Data - The next frontier for innovation, competition, and Productivity" - McKinsey This group was started to bring working Data Science professionals, aspiring Big Data enthusiasts together and engage in knowledge sharing conversations and semi-structured peer-to-peer learning environment. At the core, we aim to share our experiences and industry knowledge in 360 degree so all the members can gain insights into Big Data area. By participating regularly we will all gain a better understanding of Data Science and how the companies, economies are leveraging Big Data today and its future. There will be opportunities for presenting on various aspects of Data Science and Big Data and engage at the intellectual level discussions. This group is not just for data scientists, data analysts, students, but also professionals in finance, operations, marketing and IT and anyone interested in Data analytics and Big Data. We believe that Big Data is not just an IT related issue that has an impact on many different functional areas. So all are Welcome!!

name: Denver Redis
description: This group meets to discuss ways to use Redis to scale your website

name: Boulder Deep Learning Meetup
description: “This is a group for anyone interested in Deep Learning technology, employment, or business opportunities. All skills, levels of experience, and professional backgrounds are welcome. I started this group to help people network with one another and move their careers forward. Looking forward to exploring what this technology can do with everybody.”

name: CU Leeds Business Analytics
description:
The Leeds Business Analytics Meetup serves as an integrator for the Boulder/Denver area analytics community. Meetups will focus on cutting edge analytics research and application. Our annual business analytics conference (LeedsAnalytics.com) brings practitioners, faculty, and students together for networking and learning. Leeds Business Analytics will also offer ongoing seminars and meetings.

Follow us on Twitter at @LeedsAnalytics and #LeedsAnalytics!

name: Denver Mobile Lab
description:
We're crowdsourcing the device lab. By sharing our device collections we can build a large inventory of devices to test our web sites/apps on.

With the constantly changing nature of the web and rapidly growing mobile space it can be very difficult to test your web app/site across all the various operating systems, device sizes and web browsers. We'll be coming together as a group to share our collective experience in design/development and our personal device collections to progress the web and Denver mobile web communities.

Bring your: Smart phones. Tablets. Laptop. Game consoles. E-Readers. Handheld game systems...if it can connect to the web bring it to test on and let other test on.

For testing we'll be looking to use Adobe Edge Inspect (formerly Adobe Shadow) and/or Weinre (the free open source version of Edge Inspect) or push your app/site up to a test server to get an ever more accurate experience. There will be plenty of people to bounce ideas off of and ask questions.

Not testing? Just curious about mobile web technology. This could be a great opportunity to see first hand what is happening with the web on non-desktop devices.

The Desk Denver is generously donating space for these meetings. They have a great selection of coffee and adult beverages up front and a great co-working space in the back. Perfect for the more hands on format of this group because of the very fast, secure wifi, open desk spaces, ample seating and many power outlets. There is very limited parking in the alley behind and plenty of free street parking in the area, as well as being right off multiple bus lines in Capitol Hill area.

 

Some Resources to think about for this group:

http://mobileportland.com/

http://mediaqueri.es/

http://bradfrost.github.com/this-is-responsive/patterns.html

http://adactio.com/

http://www.quirksmode.org/

http://blog.cloudfour.com/

name: The Denver Joomla Meetup
description:
The Denver Joomla! Meetup meets monthly to discuss all things Joomla! Our topics are mainly centered around using and working with the Joomla! Content Management System (CMS) and extensions, but also include other aspects of website development, design, coding and internet technologies critical to running and creating Joomla! websites.

Joomla! appeals to a full spectrum of website users and developers from beginners to veterans and our members run the range of novice to expert in various fields of internet work. The Denver Joomla! Meetup welcomes all members at all skill levels and we do our best to provide a mix of topics from beginner to advanced. We encourage members to request topics and offer feedback so we can choose topics that are helpful to the group and make the most of our meetings.

The focus of the Denver Joomla! Meetup is not only learn about Joomla! but it is also about creating and developing a community of Joomla! users and developers in Colorado and the Denver metro area. The larger Joomla! community is a worldwide network and we strive to make our corner of the world everything it can be. We encourage members to share experiences, ask questions and participate in every way possible. Use the group to connect with one another, develop relationships and create networks that enhance our community and beyond.

Learn about the more about Joomla! CMS and download the most recent version:
http://www.joomla.org

Denver Joomla! Meetup is not affiliated with or endorsed by the Joomla Project or Open Source Matters. The Joomla logo is used under a limited license granted by Open Source Matters the trademark holder in the United States and other countries.

name: Code For Boulder
description: In partnership with local government and nonprofits, we organize grassroots, collaborative volunteer efforts to build technology-based solutions that address everyday challenges in our community. We are one of hundreds of volunteer civic tech groups that are part of theCode for America Brigade network.

name: Colorado Data Science
description:
Data Scientists in Colorado are doing incredible data science: making graph models of symptoms and human disease, extracting insight from huge amounts of data in real time, and building tools to make this whole process easier. We founded this Meetup as a forum to showcase that work.

This Meetup is organized by Galvanize, a training program for data scientists, engineers, and analysts in Colorado. Learn more or take a course at http://www/galvanize.com.

For all inquiries, including food or event space sponsorship, please reach out to Jared Polivka, Galvanize, at jared(dot)polivka(at)galvanize(dot)com.

We welcome both people working in the field as well as people interested in learning more.

name: Boulder Python
description: Boulder Python is a meetup for Python developers.  We are framework agnostic and love everything Python!

name: Mile High Azure User's Group
description: All things Azure! This is a group for AZURE enthusiasts and users. While this groups focus will be on the Azure platform, cloud computing as well as other technologies will be thrown around and tested! The group will meet once per month to showcase, problem solve and get social about the Azure platform. We will have guest speakers from Microsoft as well as other technology companies. Denver, Colorado Azure Users Group.

name: CenturyLink Denver Users Group
description:
We are users of CenturyLink, or techies interested in hands-on learning of technologies that can be used on the CenturyLink Cloud platform. We are a grass roots effort bringing together a user community interested in hands-on learning and experimentation. 

Bring your laptop, have some food and beer, and learn!  Our plan is to have meetings sponsored by independent software vendors who will help us install and run their applications in a CenturyLink Cloud environment. CenturyLink has graciously offered to provide us access to cloud environments during the meetup, so there is no requirement that you currently have access to a CenturyLink Cloud environment.

name: WSOD/MOD Alumni meetup
description: Former WSODers/MODers - you used to work at a pretty cool place with lots of very smart and motivated folks. You probably worked your ass off, shed some blood, sweat and tears once or twice, and hopefully made some friends along the way. Let's get together once a month to grab some drinks, keep in touch, and find out what great new stuff we are all up to.

name: Denver Juniper Users Group
description: Welcome to your Denver Juniper Users Group. We want to hear from you – as Juniper users, what is on YOUR mind? We seek to unite the Denver Metro Area Juniper Users to facilitate open discussions on Juniper products, solutions, direction and continued cadence of this user group. Where we go is up to you! We may even throw in some great food and beverages, now and then. Please stay in touch – We hope to see you at a DJUG event soon!

name: DeRailed
description: Denver based Ruby on Rails users group. We've been around a long time and have a great group of folks willing to explore new avenues and help people out in the ruby community. We love exploring leading edge happenings and new concepts in a cool and relax environment. Come see what we are all about...

name: Frontrange Monitoring, Alerting, & Uptime
description:
Group formed to discuss new technologies, tools, and best practices of monitoring infrastructure. How do we monitor, analyze, and alert on system actions and notifications?


Who should join: Anyone in the Boulder/Denver/Golden/DTC/FoCo area interested in the monitoring and alerting space.  It seems that there are new monitoring tools and services popping up every day.  What is everyone using?  What's working and what isn't?  Can you share stories and tips for those of us just starting to dig in to monitoring our services closely?

Why should members join: You should join if you want to learn more or share your in-depth knowledge of this kind of stuff with others in the area. 

What can members expect out of the group: Hopefully you'll walk away from each event with a better understanding of what is out there and how to use it within your team or organization.  Additionally, if you have a lot to share regarding Monitoring, Alerting, etc. ... you will hopefully feel good sharing what you have learned with your peers in the area.

name: TensorFlow Denver
description:
Does TensorFlow have the potential to become the engine behind most successful consumer and industrial products of the next 10-20 years? 

Absolutely! A much better question is how, and in what new ways, can we:

a) train more computers to teach themselves by sifting through massive amounts of data coming out of all sorts of places

b) make these computers available through an API to provide a high-quality answer to anyone who is in need. 

Why? Because everyone in need deserves the right answer. 

So.... why don't we standardize & democratize the field with and around TensorFlow, and help change the world!?

What. We are a local micro community of those interested in advancing their knowledge of TensorFlow, its use cases and applications.

How. Join our group for a regular dose of human interaction, conversations, smiles, food and drinks on all things TensorFlow:

• How-To's & Best Practices

• Tutorials

• Models

• Algorithms

• Multi-GPU Autoscaling in the cloud

• Tools & Integrations

We will learn how others solve some of the hard problems that exist in the world around us, and how others make predictive APIs and applications.

Join the movement. Let’s change the world. Because everyone in need deserves the right answer.

You are welcome:)

name: Laserfiche Enterprise Content Management ECM Meetup
description: This group is for those interested in learning more about Laserfiche ECM. This includes integration and workflows for content management automation.  Our focus is automation of on-boarding and document  process for financial services.

name: Kubernetes Colorado
description: A group for people interested in talking about and hacking on Kubernetes, Google’s solution for scheduling and orchestrating containers at scale. We’re excited about microservices, containers, the distributions that run them and the solutions that deploy, manage, and extend them. Any skill level is welcome; we’re all new to Kubernetes and we want to create an open, welcoming environment for other Kubernauts. Contact us if you are interested in speaking at or sponsoring the meet-up. We welcome content and demos.

name: Mile Hi Power BI User Group
description:
Mile Hi Power BI User Group is a community user group for sharing how to use Power BI in various environments. If you use Excel, Power BI Desktop and/or PowerBI.com we will discuss all of them and how to take advantage of them at your company.

Mile Hi Power BI User Group is part of the Microsoft Power BI User Group Program. Microsoft is not responsible for content on this website or activities that take place at Group meetings.

name: Node.js Denver/Boulder/Ft. Collins
description: This is a group for anyone who is currently using or interested in knowing more about Node.js. A great place to meet, interact, and learn with other developers, designers, managers, and like-minded individuals. Come and share your knowledge, applications, roadblocks, and get feedback from others. We'll organize regularly scheduled meetings that will focus on Node.js and many of the associated technologies. About Node.js: Node.js is a platform built on Chrome's JavaScript runtime for easily building fast, scalable network applications. Node.js uses an event-driven, non-blocking I/O model that makes it lightweight and efficient, perfect for data-intensive real-time applications that run across distributed devices.

name: PyData Denver
description: This is a group for users and developers of data analysis tools in Python. The goals are to provide Python enthusiasts a place to share ideas and learn from each other about how best to apply the language and tools to ever-evolving challenges in the vast realm of data management, processing, analytics, and visualization. A goal of PyData groups, events and conferences is to provide a venue for users across all the various domains of data analysis to share their experiences and their techniques, as well as highlight the triumphs and potential pitfalls of using Python for certain kinds of problems. PyData is organized by NumFOCUS.org

name: Mobile Dev Denver
description: The Mobile Dev Denver user group is a nonprofit group dedicated to establishing a sense of community within the mobile software development space. We do so by fostering a strong network of connected mobile developers in a bi-monthly meeting format. Our meetings are run by a board of coordinators and volunteer members. They are not a platform for individual or corporate marketing, but a delivery of a relevant, platform-agnostic, mobile software development related topic. Anyone can volunteer to present. Contact us to find out more!

name: Community Foundation TRENDS Report Meetup
description: This group is for anyone that wants to volunteer their professional skills to help visually communicate issues facing Boulder County to increase awareness.  This group is working with the Community Foundation to create the online version of the Boulder County TRENDS report. The Community Foundation is a non-profit that in the last 25 years has granted more than $68.9 million to nonprofits to address community needs.

name: Data Science & Business Analytics
description:
For folks who desire to have fun playing with data and develop both strong technical ability and skills to apply data science and analytic results to critical business issues.

A data scientist is somebody who can play with data, spot trends and learn truths few others know. Data scientists are inquisitive: exploring, asking questions, doing “what if” analysis, questioning existing assumptions and processes.

Data Science: the analysis of data creation. The data scientist has a solid foundation in computer science, modeling, statistics, analytics, math and strong business acumen, coupled with the ability to communicate findings to both business and IT leaders in a way that can influence how an organization approaches a business challenge.

Business Analytics: the practice of iterative, methodical exploration of an organization’s data with emphasis on statistical analysis.

name: Denver SaltStack Users Group
description: We are DevOps and SysAdmins that use SaltStack for infrastructure and cloud automation/orchestration, configuration management, application deployment, etc. Increase your SaltStack and DevOps knowledge by meeting other users and developers of SaltStack. Are you a SysAdmin and not familiar with SaltStack? Check out http://www.saltstack.com/community/

name: Docker Boulder
description:
Meet other developers and ops engineers using Docker. Docker is an open platform for developers and sysadmins to build, ship, and run distributed applications. Consisting of Docker Engine, a portable, lightweight runtime and packaging tool, and Docker Hub, a cloud service for sharing applications and automating workflows, Docker enables apps to be quickly assembled from components and eliminates the friction between development, QA, and production environments. As a result, IT can ship faster and run the same app, unchanged, on laptops, data center VMs, and any cloud.

Learn more about Docker at http://www.docker.com

name: Denver DevOps  Meetup
description:
Do you want to deliver quality software faster and with greater efficiency? If so, you are not alone.
However, many teams adopting a DevOps approach to software development are often tripped up by a variety
of bottlenecks which prevent them from reaching maximum efficiency – ineffective collaboration,
manual deployments, incomplete test labs,  lack of  test automation and slow hand-offs.
Join us for an interactive discussion about DevOps approaches as we bring together experts from IBM, partners, customers and others sharing how to remove bottlenecks and deliver innovation continuously.

name: Solid State Depot - The Boulder Hackerspace
description:
Solid State Depot is THE Boulder hackerspace. Founded in 2010 at a local coffee shop, we have graduated to our own space with our own tools and have developed quite the community. Have no clue what a hackerspace is? Simple, it's a place for hackers, tinkerers, artists, musicians, engineers, scientists, crafters, gamers, players and doers to get to together, work on projects, share ideas and create something great.

Come visit us at Solid State Depot every Tuesday night, 7:30PM, where we offer an open house-style meetup. Here we open ourselves up to the public to show off our space, our projects and ourselves. Whether you're a veteran hacker or are completely new to hackerspaces, we invite you to come and see what we're all about. Our members' interests range from software, hardware, electronics, woodworking, machining, welding, art, sewing, crafting, sustainability, interactivity, philosophy to many other areas. If you have an idea you want to get off the ground, if you don't have the space or tools to work on a project, if you're looking for like-minded folks, if you need help brainstorming, if you just want a place to hang out and chat, we're here for you. Other meetups include workshops, classes and other events, so stay tuned.

If you would like to become a full-time, paying member, please visit our website for more information: http://boulderhackerspace.com/dues/ Membership gets you 24/7 access to the space, access to all of our tools and supplies (with proper training), discounts on classes/workshops and supplies, and access to all the wonderful members of our community.

name: Denver NATS Cloud Native and Microservices Messaging
description:
NATS (www.nats.io) is an open source, modern and secure messaging system for distributed systems and scalable cloud applications.

It is extremely lightweight and fast, making it ideal for Cloud Native, Microservices and IoT messaging. This meetup is for people interesting in developing, connecting, and scaling distributed systems.

name: Meteor Boulder
description: Meet other developers using Meteor. Share your knowledge, apps, and get feedback from others. Meteor is an open-source platform for building top-quality web apps in a fraction of the time, whether you're an expert developer or just getting started. If you'd like to give a talk to our group, let us know!

name: Denver Millennials and Baby Boomer Co-Founders
description: For Denver Millennials and Baby Boomers who have entrepreneurial zeal and are open to co-founding companies together. Do you have an idea, but lack the vital connections, experience or capital? Join our monthly meetup to find your business co-founder.

name: CodeCraft School & Web Development Community
description:
CodeCraft School offers a variety of cutting-edge bootcamps taught by industry veterans and designed to empower students with new careers in technology.

CodeCraft School will be hosting open houses periodically throughout the year and we wanted to invite the meetup community to join us. We will be having interactive discussions on topics ranging from web development to UX design to women in technology. Everyone is invited from professionals coders to those looking to learn more about programming and everyone in between.

Our entire team is focused on empowering and transforming your future with world-class instruction, small class sizes, one-on-one attention, and industry connections that match your goals. As an extra benefit for our students, we offer free registration to all related workshops at Boulder Digital Arts that can help you prepare or fill in gaps in your new skills.

name: ROS on the Rocks!
description: ROS (Robot Operating System) Users Group in the Rocky Mountain region. There is a nice community of roboticists and robot companies along the Front Range and extending from New Mexico through Wyoming, Montana. The group will focus specifically on ROS, and ROS-Industrial. We'll have speakers, tutorials, demos.

name: Docker Denver
description:
Meet other developers and ops engineers using Docker. Docker is an open platform for developers and sysadmins to build, ship, and run distributed applications. Consisting of Docker Engine, a portable, lightweight runtime and packaging tool, and Docker Hub, a cloud service for sharing applications and automating workflows, Docker enables apps to be quickly assembled from components and eliminates the friction between development, QA, and production environments. As a result, IT can ship faster and run the same app, unchanged, on laptops, data center VMs, and any cloud.

Learn more about Docker at http://www.docker.com

name: AppDynamics Denver User Group
description: The AppDynamics Denver, Colorado User Group is an interactive gathering tailored for all AppDynamics users in the Denver area. We engage with existing customers to discuss trends in APM technology and their direction with AppDynamics, but also welcome any interested participants to join us as well. Our User Groups are technical but also people-oriented, we welcome APM experts and new users as well. These meetings are a valuable opportunity to exchange ideas, learn how other customers use AppDynamics and Application Performance Management as a whole.

name: Ansible Boulder
description: We are a group of Systems Engineers and DevOps folks who want to Ansible all the things. Want to learn more about Ansible? Come join us. Already know Ansible well? Come share your knowledge.

name: Cocoaheads Denver
description:
You Denver Cocoaheads chapter meets monthly to geek out on all the frameworks and bits involved in making Mac and iOS apps. We talk about code and technical problems and solutions. You are encouraged to bring and share your code so we can all learn from each other.

While we plan to have presentations from time to time, this group is more of a community code study group. We'll be getting down and dirty in  the code from here on in. We'll be dissecting member's code, open source frameworks, even apple's open source code, in an effort to be better Cocoa, Mac and iOS developers. Group participation is encouraged!

name: Signal-to-Noise Media Labs
description:
Signal-to-Noise Media Labs is an open interdisciplinary collective of artists, scientists, and engineers that band together to express art through science and technology. We're hackers and makers that research, design, perform, share, develop and teach with innovative, fun, and weird tech.

We're rooted in Max/MSP but explore and play with all sorts of interactive platforms and hardware. We're musicians, VJs, DJs, gamers, coders, and hackers. We've been a collective since 2011 with regular weekly meetings but have met in an non-public space so we're changing meeting venues to our own hacker/maker space. We host and participate in others art shows, hackathons, builds parties, and interactive events. Much of the time we do art for the sake of it but other times we do work for hire as contractors on independent and commercial projects. We've done work for and contributed to the City of Denver, Denver International Airport, Biennial of the Americas, Burning Man, and much more.

The group is open to all abilities and interested levels. Pros and rookies are all welcome. Even if you're just interested in any of this stuff you should come by and see what we're all about! Most of our meetings are group work time unless someone has something specific to present or we have someone from out of town visiting.

Come by and get nerdy in art and science!

name: Big Data for Business
description:
A Denver area group to help and propel Big Data, Hadoop, its extensions and its users.

Businesses need big answers, but sometimes it's hard to find the questions.

We've been working with interested Hadoopers and Big Data enthusiasts for a while, and the same problems keep rising:  How do we identify what questions to answer from this mountain of data?  With the rise of data usage (90 percent of the world's data has been created in the last two years [source:http://www-03.ibm.com/press/us/en/pressrelease/35999.wss]) there are welcome opportunities.  Along with those opportunities we have hurdles to jump, and lessons to learn.  We'll jump those hurdles and learn the lessons needed to make your data work to answer your biggest questions.

name: Innovation Pavilion: Ecosystem for Entrepreneurs
description:
Innovation Pavilion, an eco-system for entrepreneurs

Innovation Pavilion is an incubator in Denver South that offers space to accommodate startups of any size and stage.

Productive collisions and peer to peer learning occur inherently when a critical mass of entrepreneurs gather, hence the large building.

Innovation Pavilion is connecting VCs and startups on a weekly basis. We also have an extensive network of mentors that participate in our EIR (executive in residence) program. Other value adds include startup coffee shop, on-site cloud, vetted service providers and more.

Participation in our eco-system is targeted to entrepreneurs, startups, executives-in-transition and high growth companies. Free to anyone interested in being active in a collaborative environment.

name: OpenStack Denver
description:
Interested in OpenStack? Live in the Denver area? If so, then this is the group for you. We want to bring people together to talk about OpenStack, share information, educate one another, and establish a local OpenStack-focused community.

Twitter Hashtag: #OSROCK

name: Denver Data Integration Professionals Meetup
description:
This meetup provides a low key and efficient way for Data Integration Professionals in the Denver area to get together and learn from fellow members. Unlike other data groups in the Denver area, this group is vendor/technology neutral and sales pitch free. Both Traditional Data Warehousing/BI and Big Data experts are welcome to attend.

Meetings are held 4pm to 6pm every other month (Jan/Mar/May/July/Sept/(Dec First Thurs)) on the last Thursday of the month. The meeting format is a series of presentations from members in two lengths, 30min (15min presentation, 15min questions) or 1hr (30min presentation, 30min questions). Meetup is  followed by networking at the nearest bar. If you have an interesting topic that you would like present, please let us know.

Hope to see you at our next meetup!

name: Denver New Relic User Group
description:
Calling all Denver New Relic Users! This user group is designed to foster the community and connect you with the resources & peers you need to get the most out of New Relic's software analytics suite.

Some of topics we'll discuss:
- Application Performance Monitoring
- Understanding Apdex
- Custom Dashboards & Alerts
- New Relic Insights / NRQL
- More!

Each event features talks from New Relic users and pros alike, with ample time for food, drinks, networking, and discussion. This is a great opportunity to get to know and learn best practices from other New Relic users in the area. All New Relic users or those interested are welcome!

name: Denver SharePoint Meetup
description: A group for SharePoint professionals to come together and talk Microsoft SharePoint and grow their professional network. We hope to provide a spectrum of topics applicable to all SharePoint users, including Administrators, Developers, End Users, Managers, and IT Strategists. This group is open to the public and people of all SharePoint experience levels.

name: Denver Cloudera User Group
description: This is a group for anyone interested in learning and sharing best practices when using Apache Hadoop. All skill levels are welcome. Let us know if you have any topics you'd like to hear about.

name: AWS DTC Meetup
description:
For anyone interested in learning about Amazon, optimizing an Amazon environment, discussing and solving problems and more.

Hosted by Qwinix.

name: Denver R User Group
description: Our meetup is designed to bring together all of the R users along the Front Range of Colorado. We welcome R newbies as well as the experience hacker. All backgrounds are encouraged to join the group -- life sciences, social sciences, etc.

name: E-STITUENCY : YOUR EMAIL REPORT CARD FROM YOUR ELECTED REP.
description:
The E-STITUENCY initiative is a grassroots educational and activist organization that lobbies for enhanced political process by requiring elected and appointed representatives to report to constituents -- those they represent -- using email and / or possibly text messages. 

E-STITUENCY founding members believe that requiring representatives to report by email to constituents -- who they are -- how they can be contacted --  how they have voted (or intend to vote) and what legislation they favor or sponsor will motivate representatives to do a better job of representing the preferences of ALL their constituents.

The purpose of this E-STITUENCY MeetUp is to create a gathering place for Coloradans to discuss, devise and organize the means necessary to make E-STITUENCY happen and enhance voter representation and catalyze democracy.

(SEE "PAGES" AREA)

"If it ain't broke, doesn't mean it isn't sub-optimal"

name: Boulder Java Users Group
description: Boulder Java Users Group is a free, informal, all-volunteer, group of Boulder Java enthusiasts that has been meeting since November 1995. We rely on community participation. We need your involvement, ideas, thoughts, and help if we are to continue to provide quality technical education and events now and into the future! Boulder Java Users Group brings you leaders and specialists in Java technologies for first hand exposure to code, best practices, tools, methodologies, and cutting-edge solutions. Meetings are free and open to the public.  Contact Kris Woyna.

name: Trace3 AWS Meetup
description: The Trace3 AWS Meet-Up is for anyone interested in Amazon Web Services, Cloud Computing and/or the local AWS ecosphere. Whether you want to learn more about AWS or optimizing your current AWS environment, come join your fellow Amazonians over some brews to talk about EC2, S3, Big Data, etc.

name: Denver Puppet User Group
description: Join the Denver Puppet User Group (PUG) to gather with other Puppet users, and hear talks on Puppet, Configuration Management, and DevOps! Puppet is IT automation software that helps system administrators manage infrastructure throughout its lifecycle, from provisioning and configuration to patch management and compliance. Using Puppet, you can easily automate repetitive tasks, quickly deploy critical applications, and proactively manage change, scaling from 10s of servers to 1000s, on-premise or in the cloud.

name: Analyze Boulder
description:
Analyze Boulder is a community of data geeks who live, work, and play in Boulder, Colorado. Our members give fast, accessible, high-energy TED-style talks once a month on any data topic. Sign up today at speakers.analyzeboulder.com to present at the next AB Meetup!

AB on Twitter 
AB on LinkedIn
AB on Slack

name: Job Seeking Denver Java professionals
description: This meetup is for java professionals who are looking for a job. We will meet once in two weeks and discuss about how to prepare for java interviews , impress the interviewer and get selected. We will discuss technical questions and puzzles that are asked in technical interviews.

name: Couchbase Denver
description:
What is Couchbase?

Couchbase is the company behind Couchbase open source project, a vibrant community of developers and users of Couchbase document-oriented database technology. Couchbase Server is a packaged version of Couchbase technology that’s available in Community and Enterprise Editions.

Couchbase is known for easy scalability, consistent high performance, 24x365 availability, and a flexible data model. Companies like AOL, Cisco, Concur, LinkedIn, Orbitz, Salesforce.com, Shuffle Master, Zynga and hundreds of others around the world use Couchbase Server for their interactive web and mobile applications.

name: Boulder Machine Learning Meetup
description:
This group introduces CU Boulder and nearby community members to Data Science and Machine Learning. 

Even if it is not apparent, Machine Learning pervades our lives. It:

• Selects and recommends online products, movies, and web page ads

• Detects spam, malware, and network intrusions

• Performs face, speech, and handwriting recognition

• Predicts equipment failures, strokes, and network outages

• Stops credit card fraud, performs credit scoring, and detects money laundering

The goal is to prepare those interested in Data Science and with basic mathematics background for more advanced Data Science activities such as the CU Boulder Colorado Data Science Team (CODATA) and personal Data Science projects. It will cover topics such as:

• Data Science Overview

• Introductory Statistics, Mathematics, and Programming

Supervised Learning Techniques such as:

• Nearest Neighbor

• Naive Bayes

• Logistic Regression

• Support Vector Machines

• Boosting: AdaBoost

• Regression Methods

• Decision Trees

Unsupervised Learning techniques such as:

• K-means Clustering

• Hierarchical Clustering

And Feature Extraction and Dimensionality Reduction techniques such as:

• PCA

• LDA

We will have weekly meetings in cooperation with CODATA, at the CU Boulder ATLAS Institute, to whom we are grateful for providing space for our meetings. We hope it will be an exciting and rewarding experience!

name: Stacki Denver
description:
Stacki Denver is a meetup for those interested in learning about Stacki, server provisioning, configuration management, and DevOps while meeting others in their area who share the same interests.  This group is for everyone- both Stacki users and beginners to Stacki- you don't need to have any prior experience!

 Stacki is an open source CentOS/RHEL bare metal provisioning tool that can take your servers from bare hardware (or virtual hardware) to working Linux, ready to install applications. Stacki does this at scale, so deploying 1000+ servers is no more complex than deploying one. Once your servers are installed with Stacki, you can augment them with configuration tools like Puppet, Chef, Salt, CFEngine, Ansible, etc. 

Join the Stacki community: https://groups.google.com/forum/#!forum/stacki

Download Stacki: http://www.stacki.com/

Stacki documentation: https://github.com/StackIQ/stacki/wiki

Follow Stacki on Twitter: https://twitter.com/Stacki

name: Skookum
description:
Skookum Digital Works is a 10 year old, business innovation firm helping enterprise clients reinvent through the creative application of technology. We're experts at change, hardware hacking, process automation, blue sky ideas, organizational design, and finding efficiencies to both save money and create new revenue streams.

We host Tech Talks the first Friday of every month! Join us! 

We look forward to meeting  you!

www.skookum.com

name: PRE-Code School/Programming Bootcamp/Web Dev Course Meetup
description:
This Meetup is for people who are considering learning software development through one of the many Code Schools, Programming Bootcamps, Web Developer, or Full-Stack/Back-End/Front-End Software Developer/Engineer courses that have proliferated in Denver, CO.

(for example: Turing, Galvanize/gSchool, RefactorU, Skill Distillery, General Assembly, DaVinci Coders, etc.)

WHO ARE YOU? A prospective student of one of the aforementioned academic training programs. You should know that there are some essential skills and tools that can help ANYONE interested in learning how to program, write code, understand code, become a developer/engineer, make a website or app, etc. It is my belief that those skills should not cost any money to learn. So, bring your laptop (windows/mac/other) and a willingness to learn and I will show you some things.

WHO AM I? I am a graduate of the legendary Turing School of Software and Design (http://turing.io) run by Sensei Jeff Casimir who also started the program at gSchool aka Galvanize. It's a 7-month-long, 70-hour-per-week intensive coding school (they eschew the term 'bootcamp', but that's essentially what it is). They teach Object Oriented Programming, the Ruby Language, the Rails and Sinatra frameworks, client-side JavaScript, HTML/CSS/Sass, and a lot of other stuff. Before I went to Turing I knew next to nothing about programming, and now I have discovered a love and passion for programming which I hope to share with you.

WHY AM I DOING THIS? I knew almost nothing about programming before I went to Turing, and upon arriving I found myself woefully unprepared for what was to come (read: crying). I made it through the program, but it was insanely stressful and difficult to keep pace. I hope to share valuable knowledge that I gained from my experiences at Turing with you prospective developers, so that you can be more successful than I was when you enroll in a coding school. Also, if you are unsure whether or not to enroll in one of these so-called coding schools, or whether or not you should pursue software development as a career in general, my goal is to help you figure out if that path is right for you. This meetup is intended for true beginners: People with little to no knowledge of computer programming who are interested in learning how to do it.

WHAT WILL WE COVER:

Setting up your environment - Installing all the stuff you need to program on your computer and to do it well. It's a LOT of installing and I can walk you through this step by step.

Using the Command Line - I use a mac so the language is called UNIX but basically, it's that black MSDOS/Matrix screen where badass hackers in movies enter all sorts of hacker stuff. Also, it's being able to move around your computer without relying on the stupid trackpad/mouse...and to do that you need to learn keyboard shortcuts and common commands.

What is Programming? - I am no expert, but I understand how the web works, how to write a program that works on the web, common patterns and techniques for writing code, the basic building blocks of modern web-based languages, and a lot of other things that can help you really conceptualize what you are doing, so you can get the most learning value out of doing it.

Is Programming Bootcamp right for ME? - Programming is not for everyone. My aforementioned teacher Jeff likes to say that a lot. It's true. Also, it's really difficult to know whether or not you should do something before you actually do it. Wouldn't it be nice to practice, for FREE, to get an idea if this is something you can spend innumerable hours of your life doing in exchange for money?

...and other topics as they arise. You know. Basic shit. Hope to see you there! (:

name: Denver Java Users Group
description: Denver Java Users Group is a free, informal, all-volunteer, group of Denver Java enthusiasts that has been meeting since November 1995. We rely on community participation. We need your involvement, ideas, thoughts, and help if we are to continue to provide quality technical education and events now and into the future! Denver Java Users Group brings you leaders and specialists in Java technologies for first hand exposure to code, best practices, tools, methodologies, and cutting-edge solutions. Meetings are free and open to the public.

name: Beers with Engineers - Denver
description:
A monthly gathering for Denver area tech junkies. More specifically, those focused on data, emerging technology, and general IT topics. Industry vets, IT pros, nerds, geeks, tech philosoraptors, whatever.... Whether 5 or 50 this is an awesome opportunity to get together and talk shop, learn from peers, or just have some beers and a good time.

No management, No selling, No recruiting, No problems. Telling people about your product or career networking is fine but people "leeching" on the attendance have not and will not be tolerated. Industry people or those with expense cards typically be cover festivities but this isn't a "sponsored" event and we don't intend to make it that way. Venue will be dynamic alternating between locations. If the group size demands it we'll book a location to support this growth otherwise ask location staff for the BwE group.

If you're new to the group or haven't been out in a while we're a pretty dynamic crowd and always have a lot of fun.

name: Digital Analytics Association - Denver Chapter
description:
Digital Analytics Association - Denver Chapter
The DAA Denver Chapter is a local chapter for the Digital Analytics Association (http://www.digitalanalyticsassociation.org/). We are open to anyone professionally involved or interested in digital analytics and related topics and industries. Please note, the Meet Up page is public and not considered a member of DAA. All professionals are welcome to the events. Discounts are provided for official DAA members. Learn more about membership below.

Membership
DAA has multiple membership levels, with individual membership annual dues of $199 per year. Membership includes a number of educational and community benefits. To view our complete list of membership levels and benefits, please visit our website at http://www.digitalanalyticsassociation.org/members.

About Digital Analytics Association
Founded as the Web Analytics Association in 2004 and adopting the name Digital Analytics Association in 2011 to reflect the changing industry, the DAA is a member-driven, non-profit industry association. Our mission is to make analytics professionals more effective and valuable through professional development and community.

Questions?
Please contact the DAA at +1 781.876.8933 or info@digitalanalyticsassociation.org.

name: GeoDev Meetup Group - Colorado
description:
Maps in your Apps...

The GeoDev Meetup is a "technical social" where developers can meet and discuss all things geospatial, geolocation, spatial analysis, and GIS. Developers of all levels of expertise are welcome. It's right after work, it's free, we've got food and drinks for you, a bunch of Esri swag, and raffles too.

Here is our developer website where you can learn more, download and code against our APIs for free, check out apps and code samples, and use cloud-based storage and web services to support all kinds of mapping capabilities.

Also... find us on Github!

Whether you build mapping applications for the desktop, for the web, or for mobile devices, stop by and show us what you're doing.

Sign up for a 5-minute Lightning Talk and see what everyone else is up to as well.

See you there!

name: Colorado MySQL Meetup Group
description: Meet nearby MySQL Users for conversation and fun! Come to a local MySQL Meetup to talk about the world's most popular open source database, get great tips and share new ideas. All levels of experience welcome!

name: Denver DevCamp.us
description: If you love learning and think the impact the internet is making on our daily lives is just getting started this group is for you. Beginners and Pros alike are welcome to join in the discussion, ask questions and share expertise.

description: This group is for anyone interested in learning about Google Cloud Platform for Big Data. We will be providing exclusive information on Google Cloud Platform updates and announcements, share ideas and experiences, network and have a great time doing it. This meetup is a place where all website developers in Denver (or the Front Range) can meet, discuss and collaborate about everything and anything website development.  And this isn't just for developers... creative, project managers, account folk, and anyone else interested in websites are welcome!

Join the group and we look forward to see you out and about!

name: Boulder Ruby Group
description:
We’re a software users group interested in the programming language, Ruby. Our talks range from specific aspects of Ruby on Rails to metaprogamming to anything else in the Ruby world. Occasionally we may talk about software topics not directly tied to Ruby.

To keep up to date on the latest in our community join our Google Group. https://groups.google.com/forum/#!forum/boulder-ruby-group

IASA Denver is a growing chapter of IASA Global.  The goal of this group is to discuss topics related to software architecture where members will share their knowledge and learn from the group. All software architects, or aspiring software architects are welcome to join.  Members can expect monthly meetings on various software architecture topics as well as on demand meetups to deep dive into new or interesting developments into software architecture.

name: Boulder Millennial and Baby Boomer Co-Founders
description:
For Boulder Millennial and Baby Boomers who have entrepreneurial zeal and are open to co-founding companies together. Do you have an idea, but lack the vital connections, experience or capital?
Join our monthly meetups to find your business co-founder!
Enjoy the benefits of being part of an international association of Millennials and Baby Boomers who are co-founding companies... together!

name: Code Retreat Boulder
description:
Every software engineer needs to practice. Born from the attendees of Code Retreat Boulder 2011, we meet bimonthly to hone our skills working on interesting problems.

The Code Retreat format was developed by Corey Haines and others. The essence of the format is that people pair-program on a problem for 45 minutes then throw away their code, take a short break, switch partners and repeat the process. Classically, these are full-day events including 6 programming sessions, a long lunch, and beer afterwards. In this group, we will meet in the evening and probably do just two sessions.

The primal Code Retreat problem is Conway's Game of Life - it's an interesting problem in that it admits a wide variety of solutions and is simple enough that one can usually almost (but not quite) write a complete implementation in 45 minutes. While we're starting off this group working on Life (at least for the first meetup) my hope is that we expand the scope to work on other problems of similar size, complexity, and that support a similar variety of approaches to their solution. Some possibilities include small parsers, interpreters, Project Euler problems, and other such challenges.

The official Code Retreat site can be found at http://coderetreat.com for more information.

name: Denver NPUG

At NPUG we’re all about programming the network, and we host both physical and virtual meetings on related topics. Technologies and concepts like automating routers, DevOps for networks, Python, SDN technologies, and fundamental skills like Linux and basic development are what we talk about. It’s an open group for anyone to join, and we try to stay vendor neutral.

name: Denver Data
description: This is a group for anyone interested in how to make use of the data that is all around us - including business data, public data, and even your personal data. We will present use cases, demos, product showcases and training in some of the top data tools on the market.

name: Turing Community Events
description: The Turing School of Software & Design (http://turing.io) is a developer/designer training program operating in downtown Denver. We run weekly events to help grow the tech community here in Denver, in CO, and beyond.

name: Investing & Programming - A "Quantamental" Approach
description: My goal for this group is to bring together a group of investment professionals who have an interest in programming and data-focused programmers. This group of individuals will be learning about investing fundamentals and exploring how programming can be used to build useful alternative data platforms. Similar to a skills exchange, programmers will have the opportunity to learn about investing/investments and share their knowledge of programming with investment professionals to enhance the process together. For example, I have an extensive background in investments and am currently taking online courses to learn Python and want to build a network that can help me learn more about the programming universe. In return, I'd like to share my knowledge of investing to help educate programmers about investing. Ultimately, I think this group could go many interesting ways and I look forward to brainstorming with everybody!

name: Boulder Twitter Developer Community
description: This meetup is for everyone interested in working with Twitter's developer products and APIs. We organize events which aim to bring developers, Twitter engineers, and various partners together for technical talks and networking. #TapIntoTwitter

name: Front Range PHP User Group

The Front Range PHP User Group has been holding meetings since September of 2008 for PHP enthusiasts and learners of all types to get together and learn about PHP and related web technologies. We'd love to have you join us.
